sp.p:
Nay, my Lord, there can be no Objection but her want of Fortune;
'tis true, our Family has prov'd more durable than our Estate; for Fate has
maliciously encreas'd the one, and impair'd the other.

Well, I am a faithful Sollicitor; I have said more sine, moving things
to her, on your account, than ever I could say to any Woman, for my self;
and the truth on't is, I believe, shou'd prevail sooner for you, than for my self.

Hold, Hold; I cannot contain my Joy; I am convinced she loves me;
there can be no doubt of it; nay, I have been told such things before now;


but then it has always cost me so much Money: Out of pure Gratitude, I have
been forced to reward them so highly.

Ah my dear Lord! how shall I be able to requite this Favour!
I, on her Wealth and Virtue may depend;
Since I'm assur'd of both by such a Friend:

Injustly you tax me with Indifference, you know I am not so;
but you are obstinately Blind, and will not see my Love, till I have given
too much.
